<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - DRIVETRAIN FAILURE ANALYSIS - AXLE COMPONENTS - WHEEL
        DIFFERENTIAL
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="IDcomponent" graphiccount="5">
        <title>WHEEL DIFFERENTIAL</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Spinout failure. This type of failure is caused by excessive wheel spinning. Heat developed
                by the excessive speed of the differential gears will break down the lubricant film and metal to metal
                contact occurs. The pinion can weld to the cross and the cross will break (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300246">Figure 46</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300246" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300246" filename="../figg13/G1300246.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 46. Spinout Failure</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Differential case worn and scored. Excessive spinout or low lubricant level can cause
                scoring and wear at case surface which contacts the thrust washers (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300247">Figure 47</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300247" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300247" filename="../figg13/G1300247.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 47. Differential Case Worn and Scored</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Teeth on side gear broken and worn. This failure is caused by contaminated lubricant. A part
                failed, contaminated the lubricant, then caused tooth wear and fracture (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300248">Figure 48</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1300248" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1300248" filename="../figg13/G1300248.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                <caption>Figure 48. Broken and Worn Teeth on Side Gear</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Differential shock failure.</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">A severe shock load fractured the cross and pinion gears. Continued operation damaged
                    the side gear teeth (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1300249">Figure 49</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1300249" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1300249" filename="../figg13/G1300249.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 49. Differential Shock Failure</caption>
                </figure>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Inspection of the inner case shows the side gear with its teeth missing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1300250">Figure 50</hotlnk>). The gear teeth are extremely marred from the metal
                    ground into them. The fractures show a rough crystalline appearance typical of an instantaneous
                    shock load failure.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1300250" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1300250" filename="../figg13/G1300250.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 50. Teeth Missing in Side Gear</caption>
                </figure>
            </step2>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
